<body>
    <h3>Creating a New Route</h3>
    <form action="/listings" method="POST">
        <input type="text" name="listing[title]" placeholder="Enter title"> <br /><br />
        <textarea rows="15" cols="30" type="text" name="listing[description]" placeholder="Enter description"> </textarea> <br /><br />
        <input name="listing[image]" placeholder="Enter image URL/link" type="text"> <br /><br />
        <input type="number" name="listing[price]" placeholder="Enter price"> <br /><br />
        <input type="text" name="listing[country]" placeholder="Enter country"> <br /><br />
        <input type="text" name="listing[location]" placeholder="Enter location"> <br /><br />

        <button>ADD</button>
    </form>
</body>
</html>

<!-- 
    IMPORTANT: Understanding name="listing[...]" in forms ðŸ§ 

    The 'name' attribute controls how form data is sent to the server.

    When we use:
        name="listing[title]"

    Express (with urlencoded parser) converts it into:
        req.body = {
            listing: {
                title: "value entered by user"
            }
        }

    So:
        name="listing[description]"  â†’ req.body.listing.description
        name="listing[price]"        â†’ req.body.listing.price
        name="listing[country]"      â†’ req.body.listing.country

    Using this pattern groups all related fields inside ONE object called 'listing'.

    This makes it easy to:
        new Listing(req.body.listing)
        and save directly to MongoDB.

    RULE TO REMEMBER ðŸ”’:
    Only the 'name' attribute decides the structure of req.body.
